        <h1 class="govuk-heading-l">Waste Exemptions - Getting ready for change</h1>
        <p class="govuk-body">Waste exemptions are changing. The changes affect everyone who operates waste exemption activities. As an exemption holder, you must work out what these changes mean for you and act. If you do not, you risk your waste operations becoming illegal. </p>

        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">What is a waste exemption?</h2>
        <p class="govuk-body">Waste exemptions allow low-risk waste management operations to be carried on without an environmental permit.</p>
        <p class="govuk-body">Operators need to register their waste exemptions. By registering an exemption, the operator is confirming that they will comply with the limits and conditions of that exemption.</p>
        <p class="govuk-body">Failure to comply with a registered waste exemption means that the waste activity is illegal. The offence is operating a waste activity without a permit.</p>

        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Changes to waste exemptions</h2>
        <p class="govuk-body">
            Defra has published its
            <a rel="external noopener" target="_blank" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reducing-crime-at-sites-handling-waste-and-introducing-fixed-penalties-for-waste-duty-of-care/outcome/supplementary-government-response">supplementary Government response</a>
            (opens in a new window) and
            <a rel="external noopener" target="_blank" href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/1134724/waste_exemptions_government_response_annex.pdf">annexes</a>
            (opens in a new window) detailing the changes to the waste exemption regime. This consultation response tells us what the overall changes are, which exemptions will be withdrawn or restricted and the associated notice period.
        </p>
        <p class="govuk-body">
            We expect changes to the Environmental Permitting Regulations (EPR) in <b>Autumn 2024 at the earliest</b>.
            This may change as it depends on Parliament and its legislative programme.
        </p>

        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Who is affected?</h2>
        <p class="govuk-body">If you operate waste activities under exemptions you will need to make sure you can continue to operate without the requirement for a permit.</p>
        <p class="govuk-body">With immediate effect on changes to the EPR:</p>
        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>Records must be kept demonstrating compliance with the exemption registered.</li>
            <li>Waste codes and descriptions will be corrected or clarified.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="govuk-body">
            Within 6 months of changes to the EPR, operating a waste activity under an exemption on or next to (where there is a direct link) a permitted waste operation or installation will not be allowed. You must apply to
            <a rel="external" target="_blank" href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/change-transfer-or-cancel-your-environmental-permit">vary your environmental permit</a>
            (opens in a new window) to include the exempt activities before the 6 month transition period is reached. (note it is already the case that an exempt waste operation cannot operate at an installation under Regulation 5 of the EPR).
        </p>
        <p class="govuk-body">Within 6 months of changes to the EPR, the amount of waste handled on sites with multiple exemptions registered will be restricted.</p>

